    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-12-22T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-12-22T04:00:00-05:00" n="408"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d408">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72119/1034</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Switzerland</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wilson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berne</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-12-22T10:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 22, 1917, 10 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 23, 4.42 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2282. <persName>Harold F. McCormick</persName> of Zürich reports that
                    Kommerzialrat [Meinl], an Austrian visiting <persName>Prince Alexander
                        Hohenlohe</persName> in Zurich, approached <persName corresp="#p_MVC1"
                        >McCormick</persName> and asked him whether he could get a message to
                    President <persName corresp="#p_WW1">Wilson</persName>. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVC1">McCormick</persName> replied that he could answer no
                    questions. Meinl stated it would be good to know within eight days what terms
                    would be seriously considered by President <persName corresp="#p_WW1"
                        >Wilson</persName> if the Central powers openly propose them. The Central
                    powers did not care again to make proposals which would not be seriously
                    considered. <persName corresp="#p_MVC1">McCormick</persName> asked why this was
                    not brought to the United States through a neutral. Meinl replied neutrals were
                    too nervous, better for unofficial person like him to talk to some one like
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVC1">McCormick</persName>. Meinl’s mission known to
                    authorities although he came in private capacity. He continued saying
                    President’s views <pb facs="0558" n="484" xml:id="pg_484"/> not clearly
                    understood in last message. Meinl claimed to have arrived after consultation
                    with <persName corresp="#p_KRV1">Kühlmann</persName> in Berlin and was
                    proceeding to Vienna to-morrow. He told <persName corresp="#p_MVC1"
                        >McCormick</persName> if any communication was to be made it could be sent
                    through <persName>Prince Hohenlohe</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WHR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Wilson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
